				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If i lose the points i bid when i dont win, i would prefer to not bid at all. 
<br />
Actually, the fairest method is the bidding system. But it needs to be tweaked to favorize ppl who raid more. Or those who raided a few times, but from a long time. 
<br />

<br />
Indeed, some ppl complain about the system cause they cant play a lot.
<br />
When they do, they dont raid and prefer to XP. The consequence is they 
<br />
dont do a lot of raid, and when the occasion occurs, they feel they have no chance to win a loot, and it's true. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">a matter of TIME SPENT:</span>
<br />
I guess it becomes very interesting if we find a formula to integrate the number of accomplished raids, the number of hours spent on a raid, and the time elapsed between 2 raids. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">DATABASE with most targeted item by a char over time:</span>
<br />
The database could be huge. Cause for each character, we should need to know his will to win the item. So we know when someone did 4 raids during a period of 6 months, and wanted the same item but loose. He may have the same chance to win than a person who did 20 raids in one month for the same item. As you can imagine, the system is delicate and subjected to malicious ppl who may abuse of it. So, there is a necessity to manage a wishlist in conjonction with the bid/roll system. To ensure there is no cheaters. Because the cheater may change his wish, and then nullify his will over time. The legitimate casual player who doesnt raid a lot will keep the same item in high priority and will be noticed as an endurant and hopeful person during those x last months. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">WISHLIST to limit the concurrence:</span>
<br />
I saw on PABot a real good idea, but i thought underused too. It's about the priority flag on an item. It should be nerfed. The real item you'd love to have, and only this one may have the HIGHEST priority. 
<br />
Once 200 ppl have chosen their highest priority item, there is less concurrence yet. If none wished the item in high priority, we look at the medium priority, then the low one. You can manage your wishlist anytime. You can have as many item as you wish in low priority, two in medium and one in high priority. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">BIDDING:</span>
<br />
It can be done only by ppl who are present during the raid, registered, and who registered their wish (for the dropped item) into their wishlist.
<br />
The raffle has to be quick, with an internal countdown. 
<br />
In function of the priority, ppl dont know if they have a chance of success if they are not sure someone else have the same, or a greater priority. 
<br />
Stay realist, in raid they arent so many raiders at once. I won raffles i wouldnt imagine i could. 
<br />

<br />
Oh and i insist on this one, it was ok before SL, not anymore: Levels are disregarded. If you can raid, you can loot, or you dont have a point to help. 
<br />

<br />
I gave my ideas and my opinions, i dont have the key for the best rolling/bidding system. I think every method of raffle is fun and good. 
<br />
But they are limited in hard cases of overcrowded orgs and interorgs raids.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
