				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think the simplest way to do a weighted roll would be to simply take all the weights and add them up. Then whatever that value is, would be how big of a slot out of the total numbers being rolled.
<br />

<br />
Example:
<br />

<br />
You have 3 people: A, B, C
<br />

<br />
Person A has a higher level and whatever else. For the level, I will give him +2 chances, for the other crap I will give him +3 chances. He also gets a base +1 chance. So his total chances would be 6 (1+2+3)
<br />

<br />
Person B has a lower level than person a, so he only gets +1 chance for the level, and this is his first raid, so he gets +0 chances for that. He still gets the base +1 chance, so his total is 2 (1+1+0)
<br />

<br />
Person C has the worst chance, because he is a lowbie newb and hasn't been to any raids before ... so he only gets the base chance 1 (1+0+0)
<br />

<br />
Okay, so now ... you start assigning number ranges for each person based on their chance total.
<br />

<br />
A = 1 to 6
<br />
B = 7 to 8
<br />
C = 9 to 9
<br />

<br />
So now, you roll 1 to 9. Depending on which person's range it lands on, that person is then the winner.
<br />

<br />
This keeps it simple for you. Now if you decide you want to weight some things heavier than others, then maybe instead of using a base chance of 1, you make everything a multiple of 10. So base chance of 10, each raid you show up for adds +10 ... and then you can give other smaller bonuses at lesser values ... like +1 through +9.
<br />

<br />
m'kay? <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="Razz" border="0" /><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.realillsoftware.com/sigs/FeetusTissue2.jpg" border="0" />
